{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620085"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:39:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:39:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16610"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16610"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0,0.78,0.07,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66380"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9301"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51831"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3493"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5233"},{"type":"tags","id":"5438"},{"type":"tags","id":"7670"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22042"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66380"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVaccination is an important consideration for patients receiving chemotherapy treatment. Different types of vaccines have varying safety profiles in immunocompromised patients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the administration of vaccines to patients receiving chemotherapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["All vaccines are contraindicated during chemotherapy","Live vaccines are preferred over inactivated vaccines","Inactivated vaccines can be given but may have reduced efficacy","Vaccines should only be given after completing all chemotherapy","Live vaccines can be given safely during chemotherapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Einactivated vaccines can be given but may have reduced efficacy\u003C/strong\u003E during chemotherapy. While these vaccines are safe, the immunosuppressive effects of chemotherapy may result in a suboptimal immune response with subsequent reduced effectiveness. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELive vaccines can be given safely during chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E: live vaccines are contraindicated due to risk of vaccine-strain infection in immunocompromised patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll vaccines are contraindicated during chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E: inactivated vaccines can be safely administered during chemotherapy treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccines should only be given after completing all chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E: some vaccines can and should be given during treatment when indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELive vaccines are preferred over inactivated vaccines\u003C/strong\u003E: live vaccines pose significant risks and are contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor optimal response, vaccination should ideally be timed between chemotherapy cycles when immune function may be less suppressed. Consultation with the treating oncologist is recommended to determine appropriate timing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Live vaccines are contraindicated in patients receiving chemotherapy due to risk of vaccine-strain infection.","Inactivated vaccines can be safely administered to patients on chemotherapy but may have reduced effectiveness.","Vaccination timing should be coordinated with chemotherapy cycles to optimise a patient\u0027s immune response."],"references":["Kamboj M, Bohlke K, Baptiste DM, et al. Vaccination of Adults With Cancer: ASCO Guideline. J Clin Oncol. 2024;42(14):1699-1721. doi:10.1200/JCO.24.00032 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38498792/","Vaccination for people who are immunocompromised. Department of Health and Aged Care. Updated 16 August 2024. Available from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccination-for-special-risk-groups/vaccination-for-people-who-are-immunocompromised"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51831"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16610"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51831"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T21:42:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T21:42:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9301"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66380"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"descript